# MIGRATIONS

**Filenames and creating new migration files** (timestamp format, `orb php artisan make:migration`, parent vs translations order) are defined in the **NAMING** rule (`alwaysApply: true`) under **Database migration files — filename and creation**.

## Translatable models: separate migration files

For models that use a `*_translations` table (e.g. Astrotomic Translatable), **never** put `Schema::create` for the parent table and `Schema::create` for the translations table in the **same** migration file.

✔
```text
New feature: services + service_translations
→ orb php artisan make:migration create_services_table
→ orb php artisan make:migration create_service_translations_table
→ parent migration runs first (earlier timestamp), translations migration second
```

✖
```text
One file with both Schema::create('services', …) and Schema::create('service_translations', …)
```

When generating those files, follow **Creating new migration files** in the NAMING rule (two Artisan runs, correct timestamp order).

**Later schema changes** still follow **Default: edit existing migration** (below): edit the **original** create migration for `services` in its file, and the **original** create migration for `service_translations` in its file.

## Default: edit existing migration

When changing schema (add/remove/rename/change columns, indexes, etc.), **edit the migration file that originally creates that table** (e.g. `create_users_table`). Do **not** add a new migration file unless the user explicitly asks for one. This applies equally to **adding**, **changing** (type, nullability, default, etc.), and **renaming** columns — default to editing the original create migration; only create a separate migration file when the user explicitly requests it.

✔
```text
User: add column status to users table
→ edit create_users_table (or the migration that defines users), add status there
```

✔
```text
User: rename email to email_address on users
→ edit the migration that defines users, rename the column there
```

✔
```text
User: change users.name from string(255) to text
→ edit the migration that defines users, update the column definition there
```

✖
```text
User: add column status to users table
→ orb php artisan make:migration add_status_to_users_table (wrong default — edit the create migration unless they asked for a new file)
```

✖
```text
User: rename a column / change column type
→ orb php artisan make:migration ... (wrong default — edit the create migration unless they explicitly asked for a new migration file)
```

## New migration file (only when explicitly requested)

If the user clearly asks for a **new** migration (e.g. "create a migration to add status to users", "new migration file to rename ...", "migration to change column type on ..."), create it with **`orb php artisan make:migration`** per the NAMING rule — do not hand-write an empty file with a made-up name.
